<seg id=1> Chuan Leekpai: Thailand Will Accelerate General Elections </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Comprehensive sources, Bangkok, Telegram) Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai said in the evening of the day before yesterday that he will accelerate the general elections to before the term of office of the seven-party coalition government expires. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> However, he added that the coalition government is currently stable and is capable of carrying out economic reform plans.  </seg>
<seg id=4> He said these economic reforms are critical to the objectives of restoring the economy and achieving a sustainable level of economic growth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> In his speech at a banquet held by the Thailand Overseas Correspondents' Club, Chuan Leekpai said: "The confidence of foreign investors is closely linked to government stability and consistent policies. We will keep that firmly in mind." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> "We do not intent to stay till the end of the term of office. </seg>
<seg id=7> We will make use of whatever time is left to devote ourselves to carrying out reform of the national economy in order to lay a solid foundation for (future) sustainable development." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Chuan Leekpai indicated that he has not decided when the national assembly will be dismissed and when the general elections will be held. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Thailand has not yet emerged from the crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Chuan Leekpai also warned in his speech that Thailand has not yet emerged from the crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> He pointed out that the current situation is still one of "vulnerability." Global factors are likely to cause Thailand to deviate from its objective of a turn around in the economy in the second half of 1999. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> However, he vowed to implement broad reform measures and stop corruption that weakens the national economy. </seg>
</p>
